[src:gensim/gensim] Gensim is implemented in Python and Cython for performance.
[src:gensim/gensim] Gensim is designed to handle large text collections using data streaming and incremental online algorithms, which differentiates it from most other machine learning software packages that target only in-memory processing.
[src:gensim/gensim] Gensim includes streamed parallelized implementations of fastText, word2vec and doc2vec algorithms, as well as latent semantic analysis (LSA, LSI, SVD), non-negative matrix factorization (NMF), latent Dirichlet allocation (LDA), tf-idf and random projections.
[src:gensim/gensim] Some of the novel online algorithms in Gensim were also published in the 2011 PhD dissertation *Scalability of Semantic Analysis in Natural Language Processing* of Radim Řehůřek, the creator of Gensim.
[src:gensim/gensim] Gensim library has been used and cited in over 1400 commercial and academic applications as of 2018, in a diverse array of disciplines from medicine to insurance claim analysis to patent search.
[src:gensim/gensim] The software has been covered in several new articles, podcasts and interviews.
[src:gensim/gensim] The open source code is developed and hosted on GitHub and a public support forum is maintained on Google Groups and Gitter.
[src:gensim/latent-dirichlet-allocation] It is one of the most common topic models.
[src:gensim/latent-dirichlet-allocation] The LDA model was first presented as a graphical model for population genetics by J.
[src:gensim/latent-dirichlet-allocation] The model was subsequently applied to machine learning by David Blei, Andrew Ng, and Michael I.
[src:gensim/latent-dirichlet-allocation] Although its most frequent application is in modeling text corpora, it has also been used for other problems, such as in clinical psychology, social science, and computational musicology.
[src:gensim/latent-dirichlet-allocation] The core assumption of LDA is that documents are represented as a random mixture of latent topics, and each topic is characterized by a probability distribution over words.
[src:gensim/latent-dirichlet-allocation] The model is a generalization of probabilistic latent semantic analysis (pLSA), differing primarily in that LDA treats the topic mixture as a Dirichlet prior, leading to more reasonable mixtures and less susceptibility to overfitting.
[src:gensim/latent-dirichlet-allocation] Learning the latent topics and their associated probabilities from a corpus is typically done using Bayesian inference, often with methods like Gibbs sampling or variational Bayes.
[src:gensim/latent-dirichlet-allocation] In the context of population genetics, LDA was proposed by J.
[src:gensim/latent-dirichlet-allocation] LDA was applied in machine learning by David Blei, Andrew Ng and Michael I.
[src:gensim/latent-dirichlet-allocation] In population genetics, the model is used to detect the presence of structured genetic variation in a group of individuals.
[src:gensim/latent-dirichlet-allocation] The model assumes that alleles carried by individuals under study have origin in various extant or past populations.
[src:gensim/latent-dirichlet-allocation] The model and various inference algorithms allow scientists to estimate the allele frequencies in those source populations and the origin of alleles carried by individuals under study.
[src:gensim/latent-dirichlet-allocation] The source populations can be interpreted ex-post in terms of various evolutionary scenarios.
[src:gensim/latent-dirichlet-allocation] In association studies, detecting the presence of genetic structure is considered a necessary preliminary step to avoid confounding.
[src:gensim/latent-dirichlet-allocation] In clinical psychology research, LDA has been used to identify common themes of self-images experienced by young people in social situations.
[src:gensim/latent-dirichlet-allocation] Other social scientists have used LDA to examine large sets of topical data from discussions on social media (e.g., tweets about prescription drugs).
[src:gensim/latent-dirichlet-allocation] Additionally, **supervised Latent Dirichlet Allocation with covariates (SLDAX)** has been specifically developed to combine latent topics identified in texts with other manifest variables.
[src:gensim/latent-dirichlet-allocation] This approach allows for the integration of text data as predictors in statistical regression analyses, improving the accuracy of mental health predictions.
[src:gensim/latent-dirichlet-allocation] One of the main advantages of SLDAX over traditional two-stage approaches is its ability to avoid biased estimates and incorrect standard errors, allowing for a more accurate analysis of psychological texts.
[src:gensim/latent-dirichlet-allocation] In the field of social sciences, LDA has proven to be useful for analyzing large datasets, such as social media discussions.
[src:gensim/latent-dirichlet-allocation] For instance, researchers have used LDA to investigate tweets discussing socially relevant topics, like the use of prescription drugs and cultural differences in China.
[src:gensim/latent-dirichlet-allocation] By analyzing these large text corpora, it is possible to uncover patterns and themes that might otherwise go unnoticed, offering valuable insights into public discourse and perception in real time.
[src:gensim/latent-dirichlet-allocation] In the context of computational musicology, LDA has been used to discover tonal structures in different corpora.
[src:gensim/latent-dirichlet-allocation] A *topic* is considered to be a set of terms (i.e., individual words or phrases) that, taken together, suggest a shared theme.
[src:gensim/latent-dirichlet-allocation] There may be many more topics in the collection – e.g., related to diet, grooming, healthcare, behavior, etc. that we do not discuss for simplicity's sake.
[src:gensim/latent-dirichlet-allocation] (Very common, so called stop words in a language – e.g., "the", "an", "that", "are", "is", etc., – would not discriminate between topics and are usually filtered out by pre-processing before LDA is performed.
[src:gensim/latent-dirichlet-allocation] Certain terms are *ambiguous*, belonging to more than one topic, with different probability.
[src:gensim/latent-dirichlet-allocation] Most documents will contain only a relatively small number of topics.
[src:gensim/latent-dirichlet-allocation] In the collection, e.g., individual topics will occur with differing frequencies.
[src:gensim/latent-dirichlet-allocation] That is, they have a probability distribution, so that a given document is more likely to contain some topics than others.
[src:gensim/latent-dirichlet-allocation] Within a topic, certain terms will be used much more frequently than others.
[src:gensim/latent-dirichlet-allocation] In other words, the terms within a topic will also have their own probability distribution.
[src:gensim/latent-dirichlet-allocation] When LDA machine learning is employed, both sets of probabilities are computed during the training phase, using Bayesian methods and an expectation–maximization algorithm.
[src:gensim/latent-dirichlet-allocation] LDA is a generalization of older approach of probabilistic latent semantic analysis (pLSA), The pLSA model is equivalent to LDA under a uniform Dirichlet prior distribution. pLSA relies on only the first two assumptions above and does not care about the remainder.
[src:gensim/latent-dirichlet-allocation] With plate notation, which is often used to represent probabilistic graphical models (PGMs), the dependencies among the many variables can be captured concisely.
[src:gensim/latent-dirichlet-allocation] The boxes are "plates" representing replicates, which are repeated entities.
[src:gensim/latent-dirichlet-allocation] The outer plate represents documents, while the inner plate represents the repeated word positions in a given document; each position is associated with a choice of topic and word.
[src:gensim/latent-dirichlet-allocation] The fact that W is grayed out means that words $w_{ij}$ are the only observable variables, and the other variables are latent variables.
[src:gensim/latent-dirichlet-allocation] As proposed in the original paper, a sparse Dirichlet prior can be used to model the topic-word distribution, following the intuition that the probability distribution over words in a topic is skewed, so that only a small set of words have high probability.
[src:gensim/latent-dirichlet-allocation] The resulting model is the most widely applied variant of LDA today.
[src:gensim/latent-dirichlet-allocation] The plate notation for this model is shown on the right, where K denotes the number of topics and $\varphi _{1},\dots ,\varphi _{K}$ *are* V -dimensional vectors storing the parameters of the Dirichlet-distributed topic-word distributions ( V is the number of words in the vocabulary).
[src:gensim/latent-dirichlet-allocation] It is helpful to think of the entities represented by $\theta$ and $\varphi$ as matrices created by decomposing the original document-word matrix that represents the corpus of documents being modeled.
[src:gensim/latent-dirichlet-allocation] In this view, $\theta$ consists of rows defined by documents and columns defined by topics, while $\varphi$ consists of rows defined by topics and columns defined by words.
[src:gensim/latent-dirichlet-allocation] Thus, $\varphi _{1},\dots ,\varphi _{K}$ refers to a set of rows, or vectors, each of which is a distribution over words, and $\theta _{1},\dots ,\theta _{M}$ refers to a set of rows, each of which is a distribution over topics.
[src:gensim/latent-dirichlet-allocation] To actually infer the topics in a corpus, we imagine a generative process whereby the documents are created, so that we may infer, or reverse engineer, it.
[src:gensim/latent-dirichlet-allocation] We imagine the generative process as follows.
[src:gensim/latent-dirichlet-allocation] Documents are represented as random mixtures over latent topics, where each topic is characterized by a distribution over all the words.
[src:gensim/latent-dirichlet-allocation] The lengths $N_{i}$ are treated as independent of all the other data generating variables ( w and z ).
[src:gensim/latent-dirichlet-allocation] The subscript is often dropped, as in the plate diagrams shown here.
[src:gensim/latent-dirichlet-allocation] Learning the various distributions (the set of topics, their associated word probabilities, the topic of each word, and the particular topic mixture of each document) is a problem of statistical inference.
[src:gensim/latent-dirichlet-allocation] The original paper by Pritchard et al. used approximation of the posterior distribution by Monte Carlo simulation.
[src:gensim/latent-dirichlet-allocation] Alternative proposal of inference techniques include Gibbs sampling.
[src:gensim/latent-dirichlet-allocation] The original ML paper used a variational Bayes approximation of the posterior distribution.
[src:gensim/latent-dirichlet-allocation] A direct optimization of the likelihood with a block relaxation algorithm proves to be a fast alternative to MCMC.
[src:gensim/latent-dirichlet-allocation] In practice, the optimal number of populations or topics is not known beforehand.
[src:gensim/latent-dirichlet-allocation] It can be estimated by approximation of the posterior distribution with reversible-jump Markov chain Monte Carlo.
[src:gensim/latent-dirichlet-allocation] Alternative approaches include expectation propagation.
[src:gensim/latent-dirichlet-allocation] Recent research has been focused on speeding up the inference of latent Dirichlet allocation to support the capture of a massive number of topics in a large number of documents.
[src:gensim/latent-dirichlet-allocation] The update equation of the collapsed Gibbs sampler mentioned in the earlier section has a natural sparsity within it that can be taken advantage of.
[src:gensim/latent-dirichlet-allocation] Intuitively, since each document only contains a subset of topics $K_{d}$ , and a word also only appears in a subset of topics $K_{w}$ , the above update equation could be rewritten to take advantage of this sparsity.
[src:gensim/latent-dirichlet-allocation] In this equation, we have three terms, out of which two are sparse, and the other is small.
[src:gensim/latent-dirichlet-allocation] We call these terms $a,b$ and c respectively.
[src:gensim/latent-dirichlet-allocation] Here, we can see that B is a summation of the topics that appear in document d , and C is also a sparse summation of the topics that a word w is assigned to across the whole corpus.
[src:gensim/latent-dirichlet-allocation] A on the other hand, is dense but because of the small values of $\alpha$ & $\beta$ , the value is very small compared to the two other terms.
[src:gensim/latent-dirichlet-allocation] Now, while sampling a topic, if we sample a random variable uniformly from $s\sim U(s|\mid A+B+C)$ , we can check which bucket our sample lands in.
[src:gensim/latent-dirichlet-allocation] Since A is small, we are very unlikely to fall into this bucket; however, if we do fall into this bucket, sampling a topic takes $O(K)$ time (same as the original Collapsed Gibbs Sampler).
[src:gensim/latent-dirichlet-allocation] However, if we fall into the other two buckets, we only need to check a subset of topics if we keep a record of the sparse topics.
[src:gensim/latent-dirichlet-allocation] A topic can be sampled from the B bucket in $O(K_{d})$ time, and a topic can be sampled from the C bucket in $O(K_{w})$ time where $K_{d}$ and $K_{w}$ denotes the number of topics assigned to the current document and current word type respectively.
[src:gensim/latent-dirichlet-allocation] Notice that after sampling each topic, updating these buckets is all basic $O(1)$ arithmetic operations.
[src:gensim/latent-dirichlet-allocation] Following is the derivation of the equations for collapsed Gibbs sampling, which means $\varphi$ s and $\theta$ s will be integrated out.
[src:gensim/latent-dirichlet-allocation] For simplicity, in this derivation the documents are all assumed to have the same length $N_{}$ .
[src:gensim/latent-dirichlet-allocation] The derivation is equally valid if the document lengths vary.
[src:gensim/latent-dirichlet-allocation] where the bold-font variables denote the vector version of the variables.
[src:gensim/latent-dirichlet-allocation] First, ${\boldsymbol {\varphi }}$ and ${\boldsymbol {\theta }}$ need to be integrated out.
[src:gensim/latent-dirichlet-allocation] All the $\theta$ s are independent to each other and the same to all the $\varphi$ s.
[src:gensim/latent-dirichlet-allocation] So we can treat each $\theta$ and each $\varphi$ separately.
[src:gensim/latent-dirichlet-allocation] Actually, it is the hidden part of the model for the $j^{th}$ document.
[src:gensim/latent-dirichlet-allocation] Now we replace the probabilities in the above equation by the true distribution expression to write out the explicit equation.
[src:gensim/latent-dirichlet-allocation] Let $n_{j,r}^{i}$ be the number of word tokens in the $j^{th}$ document with the same word symbol (the $r^{th}$ word in the vocabulary) assigned to the $i^{th}$ topic.
[src:gensim/latent-dirichlet-allocation] If any of the three dimensions is not limited to a specific value, we use a parenthesized point $(\cdot )$ to denote.
[src:gensim/latent-dirichlet-allocation] For example, $n_{j,(\cdot )}^{i}$ denotes the number of word tokens in the $j^{th}$ document assigned to the $i^{th}$ topic.
[src:gensim/latent-dirichlet-allocation] The equation inside the integration has the same form as the Dirichlet distribution.
[src:gensim/latent-dirichlet-allocation] Now we turn our attention to the ${\boldsymbol {\varphi }}$ part.
[src:gensim/latent-dirichlet-allocation] Actually, the derivation of the ${\boldsymbol {\varphi }}$ part is very similar to the ${\boldsymbol {\theta }}$ part.
[src:gensim/latent-dirichlet-allocation] The goal of Gibbs Sampling here is to approximate the distribution of $P({\boldsymbol {Z}}\mid {\boldsymbol {W}};\alpha ,\beta )$ .
[src:gensim/latent-dirichlet-allocation] Since $P({\boldsymbol {W}};\alpha ,\beta )$ is invariable for any of Z, Gibbs Sampling equations can be derived from $P({\boldsymbol {Z}},{\boldsymbol {W}};\alpha ,\beta )$ directly.
