[src:gensim/latent-dirichlet-allocation] And further we assume that the word symbol of it is the $v^{th}$ word in the vocabulary, i.e. $W_{(m,n)}=v$ . ${\boldsymbol {Z_{-(m,n)}}}$ denotes all the Z s but $Z_{(m,n)}$ .
[src:gensim/latent-dirichlet-allocation] but the ratios among the probabilities that $Z_{(m,n)}$ can take value.
[src:gensim/latent-dirichlet-allocation] The above equation can be further simplified leveraging the property of gamma function.
[src:gensim/latent-dirichlet-allocation] Note that the same formula is derived in the article on the Dirichlet-multinomial distribution, as part of a more general discussion of integrating Dirichlet distribution priors out of a Bayesian network.
[src:gensim/latent-dirichlet-allocation] Topic modeling is a classic solution to the problem of information retrieval using linked data and semantic web technology.
[src:gensim/latent-dirichlet-allocation] Related models and techniques are, among others, latent semantic indexing, independent component analysis, probabilistic latent semantic indexing, non-negative matrix factorization, and Gamma-Poisson distribution.
[src:gensim/latent-dirichlet-allocation] The LDA model is highly modular and can therefore be easily extended.
[src:gensim/latent-dirichlet-allocation] The main field of interest is modeling relations between topics.
[src:gensim/latent-dirichlet-allocation] This is achieved by using another distribution on the simplex instead of the Dirichlet.
[src:gensim/latent-dirichlet-allocation] The Correlated Topic Model follows this approach, inducing a correlation structure between topics by using the logistic normal distribution instead of the Dirichlet.
[src:gensim/latent-dirichlet-allocation] Another extension is the hierarchical LDA (hLDA), where topics are joined together in a hierarchy by using the nested Chinese restaurant process, whose structure is learnt from data.
[src:gensim/latent-dirichlet-allocation] LDA can also be extended to a corpus in which a document includes two types of information (e.g., words and names), as in the LDA-dual model.
[src:gensim/latent-dirichlet-allocation] Nonparametric extensions of LDA include the hierarchical Dirichlet process mixture model, which allows the number of topics to be unbounded and learnt from data.
[src:gensim/latent-dirichlet-allocation] As noted earlier, pLSA is similar to LDA.
[src:gensim/latent-dirichlet-allocation] The LDA model is essentially the Bayesian version of pLSA model.
[src:gensim/latent-dirichlet-allocation] The Bayesian formulation tends to perform better on small datasets because Bayesian methods can avoid overfitting the data.
[src:gensim/latent-dirichlet-allocation] For very large datasets, the results of the two models tend to converge.
[src:gensim/latent-dirichlet-allocation] One difference is that pLSA uses a variable d to represent a document in the training set.
[src:gensim/latent-dirichlet-allocation] So in pLSA, when presented with a document the model has not seen before, we fix $\Pr(w\mid z)$ —the probability of words under topics—to be that learned from the training set and use the same EM algorithm to infer $\Pr(z\mid d)$ —the topic distribution under d .
[src:gensim/latent-dirichlet-allocation] Blei argues that this step is cheating because you are essentially refitting the model to the new data.
[src:gensim/latent-dirichlet-allocation] In evolutionary biology, it is often natural to assume that the geographic locations of the individuals observed bring some information about their ancestry.
[src:gensim/latent-dirichlet-allocation] This is the rational of various models for geo-referenced genetic data.
[src:gensim/latent-dirichlet-allocation] Variations on LDA have been used to automatically put natural images into categories, such as "bedroom" or "forest", by treating an image as a document, and small patches of the image as words; one of the variations is called spatial latent Dirichlet allocation.
[src:gensim/latent-semantic-analysis] An information retrieval technique using latent semantic structure was patented in 1988 by Scott Deerwester, Susan Dumais, George Furnas, Richard Harshman, Thomas Landauer, Karen Lochbaum and Lynn Streeter.
[src:gensim/latent-semantic-analysis] In the context of its application to information retrieval, it is sometimes called **latent semantic indexing** (**LSI**).
[src:gensim/latent-semantic-analysis] LSA can use a document-term matrix which describes the occurrences of terms in documents; it is a sparse matrix whose rows correspond to terms and whose columns correspond to documents.
[src:gensim/latent-semantic-analysis] This matrix is also common to standard semantic models, though it is not necessarily explicitly expressed as a matrix, since the mathematical properties of matrices are not always used.
[src:gensim/latent-semantic-analysis] After the construction of the occurrence matrix, LSA finds a low-rank approximation to the term-document matrix.
[src:gensim/latent-semantic-analysis] This mitigates the problem of identifying synonymy, as the rank lowering is expected to merge the dimensions associated with terms that have similar meanings.
[src:gensim/latent-semantic-analysis] It also partially mitigates the problem with polysemy, since components of polysemous words that point in the "right" direction are added to the components of words that share a similar meaning.
[src:gensim/latent-semantic-analysis] Conversely, components that point in other directions tend to either simply cancel out, or, at worst, to be smaller than components in the directions corresponding to the intended sense.
[src:gensim/latent-semantic-analysis] Let X be a matrix where element $(i,j)$ describes the occurrence of term i in document j (this can be, for example, the frequency).
[src:gensim/latent-semantic-analysis] Now the dot product ${\textbf {t}}_{i}^{T}{\textbf {t}}_{p}$ between two term vectors gives the correlation between the terms over the set of documents.
[src:gensim/latent-semantic-analysis] The matrix product $XX^{T}$ contains all these dot products.
[src:gensim/latent-semantic-analysis] Likewise, the matrix $X^{T}X$ contains the dot products between all the document vectors, giving their correlation over the terms: ${\textbf {d}}_{j}^{T}{\textbf {d}}_{q}={\textbf {d}}_{q}^{T}{\textbf {d}}_{j}$ .
[src:gensim/latent-semantic-analysis] Now, from the theory of linear algebra, there exists a decomposition of X such that U and V are orthogonal matrices and $\Sigma$ is a diagonal matrix.
[src:gensim/latent-semantic-analysis] Since $\Sigma \Sigma ^{T}$ and $\Sigma ^{T}\Sigma$ are diagonal we see that U must contain the eigenvectors of $XX^{T}$ , while V must be the eigenvectors of $X^{T}X$ .
[src:gensim/latent-semantic-analysis] Both products have the same non-zero eigenvalues, given by the non-zero entries of $\Sigma \Sigma ^{T}$ , or equally, by the non-zero entries of $\Sigma ^{T}\Sigma$ .
[src:gensim/latent-semantic-analysis] The values $\sigma _{1},\dots ,\sigma _{l}$ are called the singular values, and $u_{1},\dots ,u_{l}$ and $v_{1},\dots ,v_{l}$ the left and right singular vectors.
[src:gensim/latent-semantic-analysis] Notice the only part of U that contributes to ${\textbf {t}}_{i}$ is the $i{\textrm {'th}}$ row.
[src:gensim/latent-semantic-analysis] Let this row vector be called ${\hat {\textrm {t}}}_{i}^{T}$ .
[src:gensim/latent-semantic-analysis] These are *not* the eigenvectors, but *depend* on *all* the eigenvectors.
[src:gensim/latent-semantic-analysis] It turns out that when you select the k largest singular values, and their corresponding singular vectors from U and V , you get the rank k approximation to X with the smallest error (Frobenius norm).
[src:gensim/latent-semantic-analysis] But more importantly we can now treat the term and document vectors as a "semantic space".
[src:gensim/latent-semantic-analysis] The row "term" vector ${\hat {\textbf {t}}}_{i}^{T}$ then has k entries mapping it to a lower-dimensional space.
[src:gensim/latent-semantic-analysis] These new dimensions do not relate to any comprehensible concepts.
[src:gensim/latent-semantic-analysis] They are a lower-dimensional approximation of the higher-dimensional space.
[src:gensim/latent-semantic-analysis] Likewise, the "document" vector ${\hat {\textbf {d}}}_{j}$ is an approximation in this lower-dimensional space.
[src:gensim/latent-semantic-analysis] To do the latter, you must first translate your query into the low-dimensional space.
[src:gensim/latent-semantic-analysis] Note here that the inverse of the diagonal matrix $\Sigma _{k}$ may be found by inverting each nonzero value within the matrix.
[src:gensim/latent-semantic-analysis] This means that if you have a query vector q , you must do the translation ${\hat {\textbf {q}}}=\Sigma _{k}^{-1}U_{k}^{T}{\textbf {q}}$ before you compare it with the document vectors in the low-dimensional space.
[src:gensim/latent-semantic-analysis] LSA has been used to assist in performing prior art searches for patents.
[src:gensim/latent-semantic-analysis] The use of Latent Semantic Analysis has been prevalent in the study of human memory, especially in areas of free recall and memory search.
[src:gensim/latent-semantic-analysis] There is a positive correlation between the semantic similarity of two words (as measured by LSA) and the probability that the words would be recalled one after another in free recall tasks using study lists of random common nouns.
[src:gensim/latent-semantic-analysis] They also noted that in these situations, the inter-response time between the similar words was much quicker than between dissimilar words.
[src:gensim/latent-semantic-analysis] These findings are referred to as the Semantic Proximity Effect.
[src:gensim/latent-semantic-analysis] When participants made mistakes in recalling studied items, these mistakes tended to be items that were more semantically related to the desired item and found in a previously studied list.
[src:gensim/latent-semantic-analysis] These prior-list intrusions, as they have come to be called, seem to compete with items on the current list for recall.
[src:gensim/latent-semantic-analysis] Another model, termed Word Association Spaces (WAS) is also used in memory studies by collecting free association data from a series of experiments and which includes measures of word relatedness for over 72,000 distinct word pairs.
[src:gensim/latent-semantic-analysis] The SVD is typically computed using large matrix methods (for example, Lanczos methods) but may also be computed incrementally and with greatly reduced resources via a neural network-like approach, which does not require the large, full-rank matrix to be held in memory.
[src:gensim/latent-semantic-analysis] A fast, incremental, low-memory, large-matrix SVD algorithm has been developed.
[src:gensim/latent-semantic-analysis] MATLAB and Python implementations of these fast algorithms are available.
[src:gensim/latent-semantic-analysis] Unlike Gorrell and Webb's (2005) stochastic approximation, Brand's algorithm (2003) provides an exact solution.
[src:gensim/latent-semantic-analysis] In recent years progress has been made to reduce the computational complexity of SVD; for instance, by using a parallel ARPACK algorithm to perform parallel eigenvalue decomposition it is possible to speed up the SVD computation cost while providing comparable prediction quality.
[src:gensim/latent-semantic-analysis] the (1.3452 * car + 0.2828 * truck) component could be interpreted as "vehicle".
[src:gensim/latent-semantic-analysis] This leads to results which can be justified on the mathematical level, but have no immediately obvious meaning in natural language.
[src:gensim/latent-semantic-analysis] In semantic hashing documents are mapped to memory addresses by means of a neural network in such a way that semantically similar documents are located at nearby addresses.
[src:gensim/latent-semantic-analysis] Deep neural network essentially builds a graphical model of the word-count vectors obtained from a large set of documents.
[src:gensim/latent-semantic-analysis] Documents similar to a query document can then be found by simply accessing all the addresses that differ by only a few bits from the address of the query document.
[src:gensim/latent-semantic-analysis] This way of extending the efficiency of hash-coding to approximate matching is closely related to locality sensitive hashing.
[src:gensim/latent-semantic-analysis] LSI is also an application of correspondence analysis, a multivariate statistical technique developed by Jean-Paul Benzécri in the early 1970s, to a contingency table built from word counts in documents.
[src:gensim/latent-semantic-analysis] Called "*latent semantic* indexing" because of its ability to correlate *semantically* related terms that are *latent* in a collection of text, it was first applied to text at Bellcore in the late 1980s.
[src:gensim/latent-semantic-analysis] The method, also called latent semantic analysis (LSA), uncovers the underlying latent semantic structure in the usage of words in a body of text and how it can be used to extract the meaning of the text in response to user queries, commonly referred to as concept searches.
[src:gensim/latent-semantic-analysis] Queries, or concept searches, against a set of documents that have undergone LSI will return results that are conceptually similar in meaning to the search criteria even if the results don’t share a specific word or words with the search criteria.
[src:gensim/latent-semantic-analysis] LSI helps overcome synonymy by increasing recall, one of the most problematic constraints of Boolean keyword queries and vector space models.
[src:gensim/latent-semantic-analysis] Synonymy is often the cause of mismatches in the vocabulary used by the authors of documents and the users of information retrieval systems.
[src:gensim/latent-semantic-analysis] As a result, Boolean or keyword queries often return irrelevant results and miss information that is relevant.
[src:gensim/latent-semantic-analysis] LSI is also used to perform automated document categorization.
[src:gensim/latent-semantic-analysis] In fact, several experiments have demonstrated that there are a number of correlations between the way LSI and humans process and categorize text.
[src:gensim/latent-semantic-analysis] Document categorization is the assignment of documents to one or more predefined categories based on their similarity to the conceptual content of the categories.
[src:gensim/latent-semantic-analysis] LSI uses *example* documents to establish the conceptual basis for each category.
[src:gensim/latent-semantic-analysis] Dynamic clustering based on the conceptual content of documents can also be accomplished using LSI.
[src:gensim/latent-semantic-analysis] Clustering is a way to group documents based on their conceptual similarity to each other without using example documents to establish the conceptual basis for each cluster.
[src:gensim/latent-semantic-analysis] This is very useful when dealing with an unknown collection of unstructured text.
[src:gensim/latent-semantic-analysis] Because it uses a strictly mathematical approach, LSI is inherently independent of language.
[src:gensim/latent-semantic-analysis] This enables LSI to elicit the semantic content of information written in any language without requiring the use of auxiliary structures, such as dictionaries and thesauri.
[src:gensim/latent-semantic-analysis] LSI can also perform cross-linguistic concept searching and example-based categorization.
[src:gensim/latent-semantic-analysis] For example, queries can be made in one language, such as English, and conceptually similar results will be returned even if they are composed of an entirely different language or of multiple languages.
[src:gensim/latent-semantic-analysis] LSI is not restricted to working only with words.
[src:gensim/latent-semantic-analysis] It can also process arbitrary character strings.
[src:gensim/latent-semantic-analysis] Any object that can be expressed as text can be represented in an LSI vector space.
[src:gensim/latent-semantic-analysis] For example, tests with MEDLINE abstracts have shown that LSI is able to effectively classify genes based on conceptual modeling of the biological information contained in the titles and abstracts of the MEDLINE citations.
[src:gensim/latent-semantic-analysis] LSI automatically adapts to new and changing terminology, and has been shown to be very tolerant of noise (i.e., misspelled words, typographical errors, unreadable characters, etc.).
[src:gensim/latent-semantic-analysis] This is especially important for applications using text derived from Optical Character Recognition (OCR) and speech-to-text conversion.
[src:gensim/latent-semantic-analysis] LSI also deals effectively with sparse, ambiguous, and contradictory data.
[src:gensim/latent-semantic-analysis] Text does not need to be in sentence form for LSI to be effective.
[src:gensim/latent-semantic-analysis] It can work with lists, free-form notes, email, Web-based content, etc.
[src:gensim/latent-semantic-analysis] As long as a collection of text contains multiple terms, LSI can be used to identify patterns in the relationships between the important terms and concepts contained in the text.
[src:gensim/latent-semantic-analysis] LSI has proven to be a useful solution to a number of conceptual matching problems.
[src:gensim/latent-semantic-analysis] The technique has been shown to capture key relationship information, including causal, goal-oriented, and taxonomic information.
[src:gensim/latent-semantic-analysis] LSI uses common linear algebra techniques to learn the conceptual correlations in a collection of text.
[src:gensim/latent-semantic-analysis] In general, the process involves constructing a weighted term-document matrix, performing a **Singular Value Decomposition** on the matrix, and using the matrix to identify the concepts contained in the text.
[src:gensim/latent-semantic-analysis] LSI begins by constructing a term-document matrix, A , to identify the occurrences of the m unique terms within a collection of n documents.
[src:gensim/latent-semantic-analysis] In a term-document matrix, each term is represented by a row, and each document is represented by a column, with each matrix cell, $a_{ij}$ , initially representing the number of times the associated term appears in the indicated document, $\mathrm {tf_{ij}}$ .
[src:gensim/latent-semantic-analysis] This matrix is usually very large and very sparse.
[src:gensim/latent-semantic-analysis] Once a term-document matrix is constructed, local and global weighting functions can be applied to it to condition the data.
[src:gensim/latent-semantic-analysis] Some common local weighting functions are defined in the following table.
[src:gensim/latent-semantic-analysis] Some common global weighting functions are defined in the following table.
[src:gensim/latent-semantic-analysis] Empirical studies with LSI report that the Log and Entropy weighting functions work well, in practice, with many data sets.
[src:gensim/latent-semantic-analysis] A rank-reduced, singular value decomposition is performed on the matrix to determine patterns in the relationships between the terms and concepts contained in the text.
[src:gensim/latent-semantic-analysis] In the formula, **A** is the supplied ***m*** by ***n*** weighted matrix of term frequencies in a collection of text where ***m*** is the number of unique terms, and ***n*** is the number of documents.
[src:gensim/latent-semantic-analysis] **T** is a computed ***m*** by ***r*** matrix of term vectors where ***r*** is the rank of **A**—a measure of its unique dimensions **≤ min(*m,n*)**.
[src:gensim/latent-semantic-analysis] **S** is a computed ***r*** by ***r*** diagonal matrix of decreasing singular values, and **D** is a computed ***n*** by ***r*** matrix of document vectors.
[src:gensim/latent-semantic-analysis] The SVD is then truncated to reduce the rank by keeping only the largest ***k*** « ***r*** diagonal entries in the singular value matrix **S**, where ***k*** is typically on the order 100 to 300 dimensions.
[src:gensim/latent-semantic-analysis] This effectively reduces the term and document vector matrix sizes to ***m*** by ***k*** and ***n*** by ***k*** respectively.
[src:gensim/latent-semantic-analysis] The SVD operation, along with this reduction, has the effect of preserving the most important semantic information in the text while reducing noise and other undesirable artifacts of the original space of **A**.
[src:gensim/latent-semantic-analysis] Efficient LSI algorithms only compute the first ***k*** singular values and term and document vectors as opposed to computing a full SVD and then truncating it.
[src:gensim/latent-semantic-analysis] Note that this rank reduction is essentially the same as doing Principal Component Analysis (PCA) on the matrix **A**, except that PCA subtracts off the means.
[src:gensim/latent-semantic-analysis] PCA loses the sparseness of the **A** matrix, which can make it infeasible for large lexicons.
[src:gensim/latent-semantic-analysis] The computed **T*k*** and **D*k*** matrices define the term and document vector spaces, which with the computed singular values, **S*k***, embody the conceptual information derived from the document collection.
[src:gensim/latent-semantic-analysis] The similarity of terms or documents within these spaces is a factor of how close they are to each other in these spaces, typically computed as a function of the angle between the corresponding vectors.
[src:gensim/latent-semantic-analysis] The same steps are used to locate the vectors representing the text of queries and new documents within the document space of an existing LSI index.
[src:gensim/latent-semantic-analysis] By a simple transformation of the **A = T S DT** equation into the equivalent **D = AT T S−1** equation, a new vector, ***d***, for a query or for a new document can be created by computing a new column in **A** and then multiplying the new column by **T S−1**.
[src:gensim/latent-semantic-analysis] The new column in **A** is computed using the originally derived global term weights and applying the same local weighting function to the terms in the query or in the new document.
[src:gensim/latent-semantic-analysis] A drawback to computing vectors in this way, when adding new searchable documents, is that terms that were not known during the SVD phase for the original index are ignored.
[src:gensim/latent-semantic-analysis] These terms will have no impact on the global weights and learned correlations derived from the original collection of text.
[src:gensim/latent-semantic-analysis] However, the computed vectors for the new text are still very relevant for similarity comparisons with all other document vectors.
[src:gensim/latent-semantic-analysis] The process of augmenting the document vector spaces for an LSI index with new documents in this manner is called *folding in*.
[src:gensim/latent-semantic-analysis] When the terms and concepts of a new set of documents need to be included in an LSI index, either the term-document matrix, and the SVD, must be recomputed or an incremental update method (such as the one described in ) is needed.
[src:gensim/latent-semantic-analysis] It is generally acknowledged that the ability to work with text on a semantic basis is essential to modern information retrieval systems.
[src:gensim/latent-semantic-analysis] As a result, the use of LSI has significantly expanded in recent years as earlier challenges in scalability and performance have been overcome.
[src:gensim/latent-semantic-analysis] LSI is being used in a variety of information retrieval and text processing applications, although its primary application has been for concept searching and automated document categorization.
[src:gensim/latent-semantic-analysis] LSI is increasingly being used for electronic document discovery (eDiscovery) to help enterprises prepare for litigation.
[src:gensim/latent-semantic-analysis] In eDiscovery, the ability to cluster, categorize, and search large collections of unstructured text on a conceptual basis is essential.
[src:gensim/latent-semantic-analysis] Concept-based searching using LSI has been applied to the eDiscovery process by leading providers as early as 2003.
[src:gensim/latent-semantic-analysis] Early challenges to LSI focused on scalability and performance.
[src:gensim/latent-semantic-analysis] LSI requires relatively high computational performance and memory in comparison to other information retrieval techniques.
[src:gensim/latent-semantic-analysis] However, with the implementation of modern high-speed processors and the availability of inexpensive memory, these considerations have been largely overcome.
[src:gensim/latent-semantic-analysis] Real-world applications involving more than 30 million documents that were fully processed through the matrix and SVD computations are common in some LSI applications.
[src:gensim/latent-semantic-analysis] A fully scalable (unlimited number of documents, online training) implementation of LSI is contained in the open source gensim software package.
[src:gensim/latent-semantic-analysis] Another challenge to LSI has been the alleged difficulty in determining the optimal number of dimensions to use for performing the SVD.
[src:gensim/latent-semantic-analysis] As a general rule, fewer dimensions allow for broader comparisons of the concepts contained in a collection of text, while a higher number of dimensions enable more specific (or more relevant) comparisons of concepts.
[src:gensim/latent-semantic-analysis] The actual number of dimensions that can be used is limited by the number of documents in the collection.
[src:gensim/latent-semantic-analysis] Research has demonstrated that around 300 dimensions will usually provide the best results with moderate-sized document collections (hundreds of thousands of documents) and perhaps 400 dimensions for larger document collections (millions of documents).
[src:gensim/latent-semantic-analysis] However, recent studies indicate that 50-1000 dimensions are suitable depending on the size and nature of the document collection.
[src:gensim/latent-semantic-analysis] Checking the proportion of variance retained, similar to PCA or factor analysis, to determine the optimal dimensionality is not suitable for LSI.
[src:gensim/latent-semantic-analysis] Using a synonym test or prediction of missing words are two possible methods to find the correct dimensionality.
[src:gensim/latent-semantic-analysis] When LSI topics are used as features in supervised learning methods, one can use prediction error measurements to find the ideal dimensionality.
[src:gensim/tf-idf] In information retrieval, **tf–idf** (**term frequency–inverse document frequency**, **TF*IDF**, **TFIDF**, **TF–IDF**, or **Tf–idf**) is a measure of importance of a word to a document in a collection or corpus, adjusted for the fact that some words appear more frequently in general.
[src:gensim/tf-idf] Like the bag-of-words model, it models a document as a multiset of words, without word order.
[src:gensim/tf-idf] It is a refinement over the simple bag-of-words model, by allowing the weight of words to depend on the rest of the corpus.
[src:gensim/tf-idf] It was often used as a weighting factor in searches of information retrieval, text mining, and user modeling.
[src:gensim/tf-idf] A survey conducted in 2015 showed that 83% of text-based recommender systems in digital libraries used tf–idf.
[src:gensim/tf-idf] Variations of the tf–idf weighting scheme were often used by search engines as a central tool in scoring and ranking a document's relevance given a user query.
[src:gensim/tf-idf] One of the simplest ranking functions is computed by summing the tf–idf for each query term; many more sophisticated ranking functions are variants of this simple model.
[src:gensim/tf-idf] We see that "Romeo", "Falstaff", and "salad" appears in very few plays, so seeing these words, one could get a good idea as to which play it might be.
[src:gensim/tf-idf] In contrast, "good" and "sweet" appears in every play and are completely uninformative as to which play it is.
[src:gensim/tf-idf] A formula that aims to define the importance of a keyword or phrase within a document or a web page.
[src:gensim/tf-idf] where *f**t*,*d* is the *raw count* of a term in a document, i.e., the number of times that term t occurs in document d.
[src:gensim/tf-idf] Note the denominator is simply the total number of terms in document *d* (counting each occurrence of the same term separately).
[src:gensim/tf-idf] The **inverse document frequency** is a measure of how much information the word provides, i.e., how common or rare it is across all documents.
[src:gensim/tf-idf] A high weight in tf–idf is reached by a high term frequency (in the given document) and a low document frequency of the term in the whole collection of documents; the weights hence tend to filter out common terms.
[src:gensim/tf-idf] Since the ratio inside the idf's log function is always greater than or equal to 1, the value of idf (and tf–idf) is greater than or equal to 0.
[src:gensim/tf-idf] As a term appears in more documents, the ratio inside the logarithm approaches 1, bringing the idf and tf–idf closer to 0.
[src:gensim/tf-idf] Idf was introduced as "term specificity" by Karen Spärck Jones in a 1972 paper.
[src:gensim/tf-idf] Although it has worked well as a heuristic, its theoretical foundations have been troublesome for at least three decades afterward, with many researchers trying to find information theoretic justifications for it.
[src:gensim/tf-idf] Spärck Jones's own explanation did not propose much theory, aside from a connection to Zipf's law.
[src:gensim/tf-idf] Namely, the inverse document frequency is the logarithm of "inverse" relative document frequency.
[src:gensim/tf-idf] This probabilistic interpretation in turn takes the same form as that of self-information.
[src:gensim/tf-idf] However, applying such information-theoretic notions to problems in information retrieval leads to problems when trying to define the appropriate event spaces for the required probability distributions: not only documents need to be taken into account, but also queries and terms.
[src:gensim/tf-idf] Both term frequency and inverse document frequency can be formulated in terms of information theory; it helps to understand why their product has a meaning in terms of joint informational content of a document.
[src:gensim/tf-idf] In terms of notation, ${\cal {D}}$ and ${\cal {T}}$ are "random variables" corresponding to respectively draw a document or a term.
[src:gensim/tf-idf] This expression shows that summing the Tf–idf of all possible terms and documents recovers the mutual information between documents and term taking into account all the specificities of their joint distribution.
[src:gensim/tf-idf] Each Tf–idf hence carries the "bit of information" attached to a term x document pair.
[src:gensim/tf-idf] Tf–idf is closely related to the negative logarithmically transformed *p*-value from a one-tailed formulation of Fisher's exact test when the underlying corpus documents satisfy certain idealized assumptions.
[src:gensim/tf-idf] More recently, tf–idf variants were shown to arise as components in the test statistic of a penalized likelihood-ratio test for word burstiness based on a beta-binomial statistical language model.
[src:gensim/tf-idf] In this framework, the null hypothesis models term occurrences using a binomial distribution, while the alternative hypothesis models word burstiness using a beta-binomial distribution with a gamma-distributed penalty term placed on the beta-binomial precision parameter.
[src:gensim/tf-idf] The resulting test statistic contains the tf–idf variants binary term frequency–inverse document frequency (btf–idf) and term frequency–inverse collection frequency (tf–icf), thereby establishing a direct connection between tf–idf family term-weighting schemes and statistical hypothesis testing.
[src:gensim/tf-idf] In its raw frequency form, tf is just the frequency of the "this" for each document.
[src:gensim/tf-idf] In each document, the word "this" appears once; but as the document 2 has more words, its relative frequency is smaller.
[src:gensim/tf-idf] An idf is constant per corpus, and **accounts** for the ratio of documents that include the word "this".
[src:gensim/tf-idf] In this case, we have a corpus of two documents and all of them include the word "this".
[src:gensim/tf-idf] So tf–idf is zero for the word "this", which implies that the word is not very informative as it appears in all documents.
[src:gensim/tf-idf] The idea behind tf–idf also applies to entities other than terms.
[src:gensim/tf-idf] In 1998, the concept of idf was applied to citations.
[src:gensim/tf-idf] The authors argued that "if a very uncommon citation is shared by two documents, this should be weighted more highly than a citation made by a large number of documents".
[src:gensim/tf-idf] In addition, tf–idf was applied to "visual words" with the purpose of conducting object matching in videos, and entire sentences.
[src:gensim/tf-idf] However, the concept of tf–idf did not prove to be more effective in all cases than a plain tf scheme (without idf).
[src:gensim/tf-idf] When tf–idf was applied to citations, researchers could find no improvement over a simple citation-count weight that had no idf component.
[src:gensim/tf-idf] A number of term-weighting schemes have derived from tf–idf.
[src:gensim/tf-idf] One of them is TF–PDF (term frequency * proportional document frequency).
[src:gensim/tf-idf] TF–PDF was introduced in 2001 in the context of identifying emerging topics in the media.
[src:gensim/tf-idf] The PDF component measures the difference of how often a term occurs in different domains.
[src:gensim/tf-idf] In TF–IDuF, idf is not calculated based on the document corpus that is to be searched or recommended.
[src:gensim/tf-idf] Instead, idf is calculated on users' personal document collections.
[src:gensim/tf-idf] The authors report that TF–IDuF was equally effective as tf–idf but could also be applied in situations when, e.g., a user modeling system has no access to a global document corpus.
[src:gensim/tf-idf] The DELTA TF-IDF derivative uses the difference in importance of a term across two specific classes, like positive and negative sentiment.
[src:gensim/tf-idf] For example, it can assign a high score to a word like "excellent" in positive reviews and a low score to the same word in negative reviews.
[src:gensim/tf-idf] This helps identify words that strongly indicate the sentiment of a document, potentially leading to improved accuracy in text classification tasks.
[src:gensim/topic-model] In natural language processing, a **topic model** is a type of probabilistic, neural, or algebraic model for discovering the abstract topics that occur in a collection of documents.
[src:gensim/topic-model] Topic modeling is a frequently used text mining tool for discovering hidden semantic features and structures in a text.
[src:gensim/topic-model] The topics produced by topic models are generated through a variety of mathematical frameworks, including probabilistic generative models, matrix factorization methods based on word co-occurrence, and clustering algorithms applied to semantic embeddings.
[src:gensim/topic-model] Topic models are commonly used to organize and discover latent features in large collections of unstructured text and other forms of big data.
[src:gensim/topic-model] Beyond text mining, topic models have also been used to uncover latent structures in fields such as genetic information, bioinformatics, computer vision, and social networks.
[src:gensim/topic-model] An early topic model was described by Papadimitriou, Raghavan, Tamaki and Vempala in 1998.
[src:gensim/topic-model] Another one, called probabilistic latent semantic analysis (PLSA), was created by Thomas Hofmann in 1999.
[src:gensim/topic-model] Latent Dirichlet allocation (LDA), perhaps the most common topic model currently in use, is a generalization of PLSA.
[src:gensim/topic-model] Developed by David Blei, Andrew Ng, and Michael I.
[src:gensim/topic-model] Jordan in 2002, LDA introduces sparse Dirichlet prior distributions over document-topic and topic-word distributions, encoding the intuition that documents cover a small number of topics and that topics often use a small number of words.
[src:gensim/topic-model] Other topic models are generally extensions on LDA, such as Pachinko allocation, which improves on LDA by modeling correlations between topics in addition to the word correlations which constitute topics.
[src:gensim/topic-model] Hierarchical latent tree analysis (HLTA) is an alternative to LDA, which models word co-occurrence using a tree of latent variables and the states of the latent variables, which correspond to soft clusters of documents, are interpreted as topics.
[src:gensim/topic-model] Approaches for temporal information include Block and Newman's determination of the temporal dynamics of topics in the *Pennsylvania Gazette* during 1728–1800.
[src:gensim/topic-model] Griffiths & Steyvers used topic modeling on abstracts from the journal *PNAS* to identify topics that rose or fell in popularity from 1991 to 2001 whereas Lamba & Madhusushan used topic modeling on full-text research articles retrieved from DJLIT journal from 1981 to 2018.
[src:gensim/topic-model] In the field of library and information science, Lamba & Madhusudhan applied topic modeling on different Indian resources like journal articles and electronic theses and resources (ETDs).
[src:gensim/topic-model] Nelson has been analyzing change in topics over time in the *Richmond Times-Dispatch* to understand social and political changes and continuities in Richmond during the American Civil War.
[src:gensim/topic-model] Yang, Torget and Mihalcea applied topic modeling methods to newspapers from 1829 to 2008.
[src:gensim/topic-model] Mimno used topic modelling with 24 journals on classical philology and archaeology spanning 150 years to look at how topics in the journals change over time and how the journals become more different or similar over time.
[src:gensim/topic-model] Yin et al. introduced a topic model for geographically distributed documents, where document positions are explained by latent regions which are detected during inference.
[src:gensim/topic-model] Chang and Blei included network information between linked documents in the relational topic model, to model the links between websites.
[src:gensim/topic-model] The author-topic model by Rosen-Zvi et al. models the topics associated with authors of documents to improve the topic detection for documents with authorship information.
[src:gensim/topic-model] HLTA was applied to a collection of recent research papers published at major AI and Machine Learning venues.
[src:gensim/topic-model] The resulting model is called The AI Tree.
[src:gensim/topic-model] The resulting topics are used to index the papers at aipano.cse.ust.hk to help researchers track research trends and identify papers to read, and help conference organizers and journal editors identify reviewers for submissions.
[src:gensim/topic-model] To improve the qualitative aspects and coherency of generated topics, some researchers have explored the efficacy of "coherence scores", or otherwise how computer-extracted clusters (i.e. topics) align with a human benchmark.
[src:gensim/topic-model] Coherence scores are metrics for optimising the number of topics to extract from a document corpus.
[src:gensim/topic-model] In practice, researchers attempt to fit appropriate model parameters to the data corpus using one of several heuristics for maximum likelihood fit.
[src:gensim/topic-model] Blei describes this suite of algorithms.
[src:gensim/topic-model] Several groups of researchers starting with Papadimitriou et al. have attempted to design algorithms with provable guarantees.
[src:gensim/topic-model] Assuming that the data were actually generated by the model in question, they try to design algorithms that probably find the model that was used to create the data.
[src:gensim/topic-model] Techniques used here include singular value decomposition (SVD) and the method of moments.
[src:gensim/topic-model] In 2012 an algorithm based upon non-negative matrix factorization (NMF) was introduced that also generalizes to topic models with correlations among topics.
[src:gensim/topic-model] Since 2017, neural networks has been leveraged in topic modeling in order to improve the speed of inference, and leading to further advancements like vONTSS, which allows humans to incorporate domain knowledge via weakly supervised learning.
[src:gensim/topic-model] In 2018, a new approach to topic models was proposed based on the stochastic block model.
[src:gensim/topic-model] Topic modeling has leveraged LLMs through contextual embedding and fine tuning.
[src:gensim/topic-model] Topic models are also used in other contexts.
[src:gensim/topic-model] For example, uses of topic models in biology and bioinformatics research have emerged.
[src:gensim/topic-model] Recently, topic models have been used to extract information from a dataset of genomic samples of cancers.
[src:gensim/topic-model] In this case, topics are biological latent variables to be inferred.
[src:gensim/topic-model] Topic models can be used for analysis of music.
[src:gensim/topic-model] For instance, topic models were used to quantify how musical styles change in time, and identify the influence of specific artists on later music creation.
[src:gensim/word2vec] Word2vec represents a word as a high-dimension vector of numbers which capture relationships between words.
[src:gensim/word2vec] In particular, words which appear in similar contexts are mapped to vectors which are nearby as measured by cosine similarity.
[src:gensim/word2vec] This indicates the level of semantic similarity between the words, so for example the vectors for *walk* and *ran* are nearby, as are those for "but" and "however", and "Berlin" and "Germany".
[src:gensim/word2vec] Word2vec is a group of related models that are used to produce word embeddings.
[src:gensim/word2vec] These models are shallow, two-layer neural networks that are trained to reconstruct linguistic contexts of words.
[src:gensim/word2vec] Word2vec takes as its input a large corpus of text and produces a mapping of the set of words to a vector space, typically of several hundred dimensions, with each unique word in the corpus being assigned a vector in the space.
[src:gensim/word2vec] Word2vec can use either of two model architectures to produce these distributed representations of words: continuous bag of words (CBOW) or continuously sliding skip-gram.
[src:gensim/word2vec] In both architectures, word2vec considers both individual words and a sliding context window as it iterates over the corpus.
[src:gensim/word2vec] The CBOW can be viewed as a 'fill in the blank' task, where the word embedding represents the way the word influences the relative probabilities of other words in the context window.
[src:gensim/word2vec] Words which are semantically similar should influence these probabilities in similar ways, because semantically similar words should be used in similar contexts.
[src:gensim/word2vec] The order of context words does not influence prediction (bag of words assumption).
[src:gensim/word2vec] In the continuous skip-gram architecture, the model uses the current word to predict the surrounding window of context words.
[src:gensim/word2vec] The skip-gram architecture weighs nearby context words more heavily than more distant context words.
[src:gensim/word2vec] According to the authors' note, CBOW is faster while skip-gram does a better job for infrequent words.
[src:gensim/word2vec] After the model is trained, the learned word embeddings are positioned in the vector space such that words that share common contexts in the corpus — that is, words that are semantically and syntactically similar — are located close to one another in the space.
[src:gensim/word2vec] More dissimilar words are located farther from one another in the space.
[src:gensim/word2vec] Both CBOW and skip-gram are methods to learn one vector per word appearing in the corpus.
[src:gensim/word2vec] Let V ("vocabulary") be the set of all words appearing in the corpus C .
[src:gensim/word2vec] Our goal is to learn one vector $v_{w}\in \mathbb {R} ^{d}$ for each word $w\in V$ .
[src:gensim/word2vec] The idea of skip-gram is that the vector of a word should be close to the vector of each of its neighbors.
[src:gensim/word2vec] The idea of CBOW is that the vector-sum of a word's neighbors should be close to the vector of the word.
[src:gensim/word2vec] The idea of CBOW is to represent each word with a vector, such that it is possible to predict a word using the sum of the vectors of its neighbors.
[src:gensim/word2vec] Specifically, for each word $w_{i}$ in the corpus, the one-hot encoding of the word is used as the input to the neural network.
[src:gensim/word2vec] The output of the neural network is a probability distribution over the dictionary, representing a prediction of individual words in the neighborhood of $w_{i}$ .
[src:gensim/word2vec] The objective of training is to maximize $\sum _{i}\ln \Pr(w_{i}\mid w_{i+j}\colon j\in N)$ where N is a set of (non-zero) indices representing the relative locations of nearby words considered to be in $w_{i}$ 's neighborhood.
[src:gensim/word2vec] For example, if we want each word in the corpus to be predicted by every other word in a small span of 4 words.
[src:gensim/word2vec] In standard bag-of-words, a word's context is represented by a word-count (aka a word histogram) of its neighboring words.
[src:gensim/word2vec] For example, the "sat" in "the cat sat on the mat" is represented as {"the": 2, "cat": 1, "on": 1}.
[src:gensim/word2vec] Note that the last word "mat" is not used to represent "sat", because it is outside the neighborhood $N=\{-2,-1,+1,+2\}$ .
[src:gensim/word2vec] In continuous bag-of-words, the histogram is multiplied by a matrix V to obtain a continuous representation of the word's context.
[src:gensim/word2vec] The matrix V is also called a **dictionary**.
[src:gensim/word2vec] It has D columns, where D is the size of the dictionary.
[src:gensim/word2vec] Let d be the length of each word vector.
[src:gensim/word2vec] We have $V\in \mathbb {R} ^{d\times D}$ .
[src:gensim/word2vec] This is then multiplied with another matrix $V'$ of shape $\mathbb {R} ^{D\times d}$ .
[src:gensim/word2vec] This results in a vector of length D , one entry per dictionary entry.
[src:gensim/word2vec] Then, apply the softmax to obtain a probability distribution over the dictionary.
[src:gensim/word2vec] This system can be visualized as a neural network, similar in spirit to an autoencoder, of architecture linear-linear-softmax, as depicted in the diagram.
[src:gensim/word2vec] The system is trained by gradient descent to minimize the cross-entropy loss.
[src:gensim/word2vec] Once such a system is trained, we have two trained matrices $V,V'$ .
[src:gensim/word2vec] Either the column vectors of V or the row vectors of $V'$ can serve as the dictionary.
[src:gensim/word2vec] For example, the word "sat" can be represented as either the "sat"-th column of V or the "sat"-th row of $V'$ .
[src:gensim/word2vec] It is also possible to simply define $V'=V^{\top }$ , in which case there would no longer be a choice.
[src:gensim/word2vec] The idea of skip-gram is to represent each word with a vector, such that it is possible to predict the vectors of its neighbors using the vector of a word.
[src:gensim/word2vec] The architecture is still linear-linear-softmax, the same as CBOW, but the input and the output are switched.
[src:gensim/word2vec] The objective of training is to maximize $\sum _{i}\sum _{j\in N}\ln \Pr(w_{j+i}\mid w_{i})$ .
[src:gensim/word2vec] Essentially, skip-gram and CBOW are exactly the same in architecture.
[src:gensim/word2vec] They only differ in the objective function during training.
[src:gensim/word2vec] During the 1980s, there were some early attempts at using neural networks to represent words and concepts as vectors.
[src:gensim/word2vec] In 2010, Tomáš Mikolov (then at Brno University of Technology) with co-authors applied a simple recurrent neural network with a single hidden layer to language modelling.
[src:gensim/word2vec] Word2vec was created, patented, and published in 2013 by a team of researchers led by Mikolov at Google over two papers.
[src:gensim/word2vec] The original paper was rejected by reviewers for ICLR conference 2013.
[src:gensim/word2vec] It also took months for the code to be approved for open-sourcing.
[src:gensim/word2vec] Other researchers helped analyse and explain the algorithm.
[src:gensim/word2vec] Embedding vectors created using the Word2vec algorithm have some advantages compared to earlier algorithms such as those using n-grams and latent semantic analysis.
[src:gensim/word2vec] GloVe was developed by a team at Stanford specifically as a competitor, and the original paper noted multiple improvements of GloVe over word2vec.
[src:gensim/word2vec] Mikolov argued that the comparison was unfair as GloVe was trained on more data, and that the fastText project showed that word2vec is superior when trained on the same data.
[src:gensim/word2vec] As of 2022, the straight Word2vec approach was described as "dated".
[src:gensim/word2vec] Transformer-based models, such as ELMo and BERT, which add multiple neural-network attention layers on top of a word embedding model similar to Word2vec, have come to be regarded as the state of the art in natural language processing.
[src:gensim/word2vec] Results of word2vec training can be sensitive to parametrization.
[src:gensim/word2vec] The following are some important parameters in word2vec training.
[src:gensim/word2vec] A word2vec model can be trained with hierarchical softmax and/or negative sampling.
[src:gensim/word2vec] To approximate the conditional log-likelihood a model seeks to maximize, the hierarchical softmax method uses a Huffman tree to reduce calculation.
[src:gensim/word2vec] The negative sampling method, on the other hand, approaches the maximization problem by minimizing the log-likelihood of sampled negative instances.
[src:gensim/word2vec] According to the authors, hierarchical softmax works better for infrequent words while negative sampling works better for frequent words and better with low dimensional vectors.
[src:gensim/word2vec] As training epochs increase, hierarchical softmax stops being useful.
[src:gensim/word2vec] High-frequency and low-frequency words often provide little information.
[src:gensim/word2vec] Words with a frequency above a certain threshold, or below a certain threshold, may be subsampled or removed to speed up training.
[src:gensim/word2vec] Quality of word embedding increases with higher dimensionality.
[src:gensim/word2vec] But after reaching some point, marginal gain diminishes.
[src:gensim/word2vec] Typically, the dimensionality of the vectors is set to be between 100 and 1,000.
[src:gensim/word2vec] The size of the context window determines how many words before and after a given word are included as context words of the given word.
[src:gensim/word2vec] According to the authors' note, the recommended value is 10 for skip-gram and 5 for CBOW.
[src:gensim/word2vec] There are a variety of extensions to word2vec.
[src:gensim/word2vec] doc2vec estimates the distributed representations of documents much like how word2vec estimates representations of words: doc2vec utilizes either of two model architectures, both of which are allegories to the architectures used in word2vec.
[src:gensim/word2vec] The first, Distributed Memory Model of Paragraph Vectors (PV-DM), is identical to CBOW other than it also provides a unique document identifier as a piece of additional context.
[src:gensim/word2vec] The second architecture, Distributed Bag of Words version of Paragraph Vector (PV-DBOW), is identical to the skip-gram model except that it attempts to predict the window of surrounding context words from the paragraph identifier instead of the current word.
[src:gensim/word2vec] doc2vec also has the ability to capture the semantic 'meanings' for additional pieces of 'context' around words; doc2vec can estimate the semantic embeddings for speakers or speaker attributes, groups, and periods of time.
[src:gensim/word2vec] For example, doc2vec has been used to estimate the political positions of political parties in various Congresses and Parliaments in the U.S. and U.K., respectively, and various governmental institutions.
[src:gensim/word2vec] Another extension of word2vec is top2vec, which leverages both document and word embeddings to estimate distributed representations of topics. top2vec takes document embeddings learned from a doc2vec model and reduces them into a lower dimension (typically using UMAP).
[src:gensim/word2vec] The space of documents is then scanned using HDBSCAN, and clusters of similar documents are found.
[src:gensim/word2vec] Next, the centroid of documents identified in a cluster is considered to be that cluster's topic vector.
[src:gensim/word2vec] Finally, top2vec searches the semantic space for word embeddings located near to the topic vector to ascertain the 'meaning' of the topic.
[src:gensim/word2vec] The word with embeddings most similar to the topic vector might be assigned as the topic's title, whereas far away word embeddings may be considered unrelated.
[src:gensim/word2vec] As opposed to other topic models such as LDA, top2vec provides canonical 'distance' metrics between two topics, or between a topic and another embeddings (word, document, or otherwise).
[src:gensim/word2vec] Together with results from HDBSCAN, users can generate topic hierarchies, or groups of related topics and subtopics.
[src:gensim/word2vec] Furthermore, a user can use the results of top2vec to infer the topics of out-of-sample documents.
[src:gensim/word2vec] After inferring the embedding for a new document, must only search the space of topics for the closest topic vector.
[src:gensim/word2vec] An extension of word vectors for n-grams in biological sequences (e.g.
[src:gensim/word2vec] DNA, RNA, and proteins) for bioinformatics applications has been proposed by Asgari and Mofrad.
[src:gensim/word2vec] Named bio-vectors (BioVec) to refer to biological sequences in general with protein-vectors (ProtVec) for proteins (amino-acid sequences) and gene-vectors (GeneVec) for gene sequences, this representation can be widely used in applications of machine learning in proteomics and genomics.
[src:gensim/word2vec] The results suggest that BioVectors can characterize biological sequences in terms of biochemical and biophysical interpretations of the underlying patterns.
[src:gensim/word2vec] A similar variant, dna2vec, has shown that there is correlation between Needleman–Wunsch similarity score and cosine similarity of dna2vec word vectors.
[src:gensim/word2vec] An extension of word vectors for creating a dense vector representation of unstructured radiology reports has been proposed by Banerjee et al.
[src:gensim/word2vec] One of the biggest challenges with Word2vec is how to handle unknown or out-of-vocabulary (OOV) words and morphologically similar words.
[src:gensim/word2vec] If the Word2vec model has not encountered a particular word before, it will be forced to use a random vector, which is generally far from its ideal representation.
[src:gensim/word2vec] This can particularly be an issue in domains like medicine where synonyms and related words can be used depending on the preferred style of radiologist, and words may have been used infrequently in a large corpus.
[src:gensim/word2vec] Of particular interest, the IWE model (trained on the one institutional dataset) successfully translated to a different institutional dataset which demonstrates good generalizability of the approach across institutions.
[src:gensim/word2vec] The reasons for successful word embedding learning in the word2vec framework are poorly understood.
[src:gensim/word2vec] Goldberg and Levy point out that the word2vec objective function causes words that occur in similar contexts to have similar embeddings (as measured by cosine similarity) and note that this is in line with J.
[src:gensim/word2vec] However, they note that this explanation is "very hand-wavy" and argue that a more formal explanation would be preferable.
[src:gensim/word2vec] (2015) show that much of the superior performance of word2vec or similar embeddings in downstream tasks is not a result of the models per se, but of the choice of specific hyperparameters.
[src:gensim/word2vec] Transferring these hyperparameters to more 'traditional' approaches yields similar performances in downstream tasks.
[src:gensim/word2vec] (2016) explain word2vec and related algorithms as performing inference for a simple generative model for text, which involves a random walk generation process based upon loglinear topic model.
[src:gensim/word2vec] They use this to explain some properties of word embeddings, including their use to solve analogies.
[src:gensim/word2vec] The word embedding approach is able to capture multiple different degrees of similarity between words.
[src:gensim/word2vec] (2013) found that semantic and syntactic patterns can be reproduced using vector arithmetic.
[src:gensim/word2vec] Such relationships can be generated for a range of semantic relations (such as Country–Capital) as well as syntactic relations (e.g. present tense–past tense).
[src:gensim/word2vec] This facet of word2vec has been exploited in a variety of other contexts.
[src:gensim/word2vec] For example, word2vec has been used to map a vector space of words in one language to a vector space constructed from another language.
[src:gensim/word2vec] Relationships between translated words in both spaces can be used to assist with machine translation of new words.
[src:gensim/word2vec] (2013) developed an approach to assessing the quality of a word2vec model which draws on the semantic and syntactic patterns discussed above.
[src:gensim/word2vec] They developed a set of 8,869 semantic relations and 10,675 syntactic relations which they use as a benchmark to test the accuracy of a model.
[src:gensim/word2vec] When assessing the quality of a vector model, a user may draw on this accuracy test which is implemented in word2vec, or develop their own test set which is meaningful to the corpora which make up the model.
[src:gensim/word2vec] This approach offers a more challenging test than simply arguing that the words most similar to a given test word are intuitively plausible.
[src:gensim/word2vec] The use of different model parameters and different corpus sizes can greatly affect the quality of a word2vec model.
[src:gensim/word2vec] Accuracy can be improved in a number of ways, including the choice of model architecture (CBOW or Skip-Gram), increasing the training data set, increasing the number of vector dimensions, and increasing the window size of words considered by the algorithm.
[src:gensim/word2vec] Each of these improvements comes with the cost of increased computational complexity and therefore increased model generation time.
[src:gensim/word2vec] In models using large corpora and a high number of dimensions, the skip-gram model yields the highest overall accuracy, and consistently produces the highest accuracy on semantic relationships, as well as yielding the highest syntactic accuracy in most cases.
[src:gensim/word2vec] However, the CBOW is less computationally expensive and yields similar accuracy results.
[src:gensim/word2vec] Overall, accuracy increases with the number of words used and the number of dimensions.
[src:gensim/word2vec] Mikolov et al. report that doubling the amount of training data results in an increase in computational complexity equivalent to doubling the number of vector dimensions.
[src:gensim/word2vec] Altszyler and coauthors (2017) studied Word2vec performance in two semantic tests for different corpus size.
[src:gensim/word2vec] They found that Word2vec has a steep learning curve, outperforming another word-embedding technique, latent semantic analysis (LSA), when it is trained with medium to large corpus size (more than 10 million words).
[src:gensim/word2vec] However, with a small training corpus, LSA showed better performance.
[src:gensim/word2vec] Additionally they show that the best parameter setting depends on the task and the training corpus.
[src:gensim/word2vec] Nevertheless, for skip-gram models trained in medium size corpora, with 50 dimensions, a window size of 15 and 10 negative samples seems to be a good parameter setting.
